    "abstract": "<jats:p> This paper proposes foundations and a methodology for survey-based tracking of well-being. First, we develop a theory in which utility depends on \u201cfundamental aspects\u201d of well-being, measurable with surveys. Second, drawing from psychologists, philosophers, and economists, we compile a comprehensive list of such aspects. Third, we demonstrate our proposed method for estimating the aspects' relative marginal utilities\u2014a necessary input for constructing an individual-level well-being index\u2014by asking \u223c4,600 US survey respondents to state their preference between pairs of aspect bundles. We estimate high relative marginal utilities for aspects related to family, health, security, values, freedom, happiness, and life satisfaction. (JEL C43, C83, D12, I31) </jats:p>",
